Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/21/2026
Notes: Gothic period live-action. One medium throughout. Pale candlelight, deep shadows, tight interiors.

FADE IN:

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

A single chair. A bare table. Candlelight. Period walls, no ornament.

THE NARRATOR sits facing us—middle-aged, gaunt, pale skin, dark disordered hair, sharp restless eyes, plain dark coat and waistcoat of the 1840s. Hands too still, then suddenly not.

He speaks with careful calm—too careful.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He leans a fraction closer.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night. Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his eye! yes, it was this!

INT. OLD MAN'S SITTING ROOM - DAY

Dusty gentility. Heavy curtains half-drawn. An elderly man in a worn dressing gown—THE OLD MAN, thin, white-haired, mild—turns in his chair.

One eye is pale blue, filmed, vulture-like. It catches the light.

THE NARRATOR (younger by the week of the crime, same face, neater coat) freezes as that eye falls on him. His blood runs cold in his face.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold; and so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

The Old Man smiles faintly, unaware. The Narrator forces a gentle nod and pours the old man's tea with exaggerated care.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

The Narrator on the chair again, a thin smile of pride.

NARRATOR
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

INT. HALLWAY OUTSIDE BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Midnight. A dark lantern, closed, in the Narrator's hands. He turns the latch—oh, so gently—and opens the door a crack.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And every night, about midnight, I turned the latch of his door and opened it—oh, so gently!

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Pitch dark. Shutters fastened. The Old Man asleep under heavy covers—a pale shape on the bed.

The Narrator's head eases through the opening, then the dark lantern, all closed. He moves with painful slowness.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And then, when I had made an opening sufficient for my head, I put in a dark lantern, all closed, closed, that no light shone out, and then I thrust in my head. I moved it slowly—very, very slowly, so that I might not disturb the old man's sleep. It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed.

A hinge creaks as he undoes the lantern a hair. A single thin ray seeks the pillow—finds the eye shut.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Ha!—would a madman have been so wise as this? And then I undid the lantern cautiously—oh, so cautiously—cautiously (for the hinges creaked)—I undid it just so much that a single thin ray fell upon the vulture eye. And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

He eases back. The ray dies. The door whispers shut.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - DAY

Morning light through a gap in the shutters. The Narrator enters boldly, hearty, kind.

NARRATOR
And how have you passed the night?

The Old Man, seated on the bed's edge, answers with sleepy gratitude—no suspicion. The filmed eye is open but mild in daylight. The Narrator meets it and does not flinch—smiling, courageous.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Every morning, when the day broke, I went boldly into the chamber, and spoke courageously to him, calling him by name in a hearty tone. So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

The Narrator’s hands knit, then open—triumph remembered.

NARRATOR
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. A watch’s minute hand moves more quickly than did mine. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph.

INT. HALLWAY OUTSIDE BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

The eighth night. The Narrator at the door, pushing it by degrees—little by little. A private chuckle escapes him.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Black as pitch. The Old Man stirs suddenly on the bed, startled.

The Narrator does not draw back. He keeps pushing the door—steadily, steadily—head in, lantern ready.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
To think that there I was, opening the door, little by little, and he not even to dream of my secret deeds or thoughts. I fairly chuckled at the idea; and perhaps he heard me; for he moved on the bed suddenly, as if startled. Now you may think that I drew back—but no. His room was as black as pitch with the thick darkness, for the shutters were close fastened, through fear of robbers, and so I knew that he could not see the opening of the door.

His thumb slips on the tin fastening of the lantern.

A small metallic sound.

The Old Man springs up in bed.

OLD MAN
Who’s there?

Silence. The Narrator frozen in the opening—does not move a muscle.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

A slight groan—low, stifled—mortal terror, not pain.

The Old Man sits rigid in the dark, listening, whispering to himself.

OLD MAN
(whispered, to himself)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal terror. It was not a groan of pain or of grief—oh, no!—it was the low stifled sound that arises from the bottom of the soul when overcharged with awe. I knew the sound well. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled at heart. Death, in approaching him, had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

The Narrator waits—a long time—patient. Then, stealthily, he opens a very little crevice in the lantern.

A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open—wide, wide open.

The Narrator’s face, in almost no light, goes furious as he gazes. The ray holds on the dull blue eye and its hideous veil—nothing else of the face.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It was open—wide, wide open—and I grew furious as I gazed upon it. I saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones; but I could see nothing else of the old man’s face or person: for I had directed the ray as if by instinct, precisely upon the damned spot.

A low, dull, quick sound—such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. Soft at first. Then clearer.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And have I not told you that what you mistake for madness is but over-acuteness of the sense?—now, I say, there came to my ears a low, dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man’s heart. It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier into courage.

He scarcely breathes. Lantern motionless. Ray steady on the eye.

The heartbeat grows quicker—louder—louder.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But even yet I refrained and kept still. Meantime the hellish tattoo of the heart increased. It grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant. The old man’s terror must have been extreme! It grew louder, I say, louder every moment!—do you mark me well?

The sound swells in the dreadful silence of the old house. The Narrator’s eyes widen—terror under the fury.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror. Yet, for some minutes longer I refrained and stood still. But the beating grew louder, louder! I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man’s hour had come!

A loud yell. He throws open the lantern—light floods—and leaps into the room.

The Old Man shrieks once—once only.

In an instant the Narrator drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him.

The Narrator stands, smiling gaily, chest heaving.

Beneath the bed: a muffled heartbeat. Many minutes. The Narrator listens, head tilted—still smiling.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then smiled gaily, to find the deed so far done. But, for many minutes, the heart beat on with a muffled sound. This, however, did not vex me; it would not be heard through the wall.

The muffled beat falters—slows—ceases.

Silence.

He removes the bed. Examines the corpse. Places his hand upon the heart and holds it there—many minutes. No pulsation.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
At length it ceased. The old man was dead. I removed the bed and examined the corpse. Yes, he was stone, stone dead. I placed my hand upon the heart and held it there many minutes. There was no pulsation. He was stone dead. His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

The Narrator’s smile is bright, instructional—almost merry.

NARRATOR
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body. The night waned, and I worked hastily, but in silence.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Candle. A tub. The Narrator works in silence—dismembers the corpse: head, arms, legs. We see enough—shadow, the saw’s motion, the tub catching what falls—never lingering for spectacle.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
First of all I dismembered the corpse. I cut off the head and the arms and the legs.

He pries up three planks from the flooring. Deposits the remains between the scantlings. Replaces the boards with cunning care—presses the seams. No stain. He glances at the tub—a short, sharp laugh.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then took up three planks from the flooring of the chamber, and deposited all between the scantlings. I then replaced the boards so cleverly, so cunningly, that no human eye—not even his—could have detected any thing wrong. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had caught all—ha! ha!

Somewhere below, a clock bell sounds four.

A knocking at the street door.

INT. ENTRY HALL - NIGHT

Still dark as midnight. The Narrator opens the door with a light heart—candle raised.

Three men in police coats and badges of the period:

OFFICER REYNOLDS — senior, calm, solid build, greying beard.
OFFICER HALE — younger, sharp-eyed, clean-shaven.
OFFICER BRENNAN — broad, quiet, watchful.

REYNOLDS
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play has been aroused. We have been deputed to search the premises.

The Narrator smiles—bows them in.

NARRATOR
Gentlemen—welcome. The shriek was my own, in a dream. The old man is absent in the country. Search—search well.

INT. OLD MAN'S HOUSE - HALL AND SITTING ROOM - NIGHT

He leads them through—opens cupboards, lifts cloths, shows undisturbed rooms. Confidence blooming into showmanship. Reynolds, Hale, and Brennan exchange glances—satisfied, almost bored.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

The Narrator ushers them in. Shows the Old Man’s treasures—secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of his confidence he brings chairs and sets them.

He places his own seat upon the very spot beneath which the corpse reposes—and sits.

NARRATOR
Rest from your fatigues. You see—all is well.

The officers sit. They chat of familiar things. The Narrator answers cheerily—singularly at ease.

REYNOLDS
Quiet street, as a rule.

HALE
Neighbour was certain of a cry. These old houses carry sound.

BRENNAN
No sign of a struggle. You’ll forgive the hour.

NARRATOR
Of course—of course. Search wherever you please.

Ere long his face pales. He touches his temple. A faint ringing—his eyes flick once toward the floor, then away.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But, ere long, I felt myself getting pale and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears: but still they sat and still chatted. The ringing became more distinct:—it continued and became more distinct: I talked more freely to get rid of the feeling: but it continued and gained definiteness—until, at length, I found that the noise was not within my ears.

A low, dull, quick sound—watch-in-cotton—rises from beneath the floorboards. Soft. Steady. Growing.

The officers do not react. They smile. They chat.

The Narrator talks more fluently—heightened voice—gestures too wide.

NARRATOR
The beams—solid work—no damp—excellent house—

The sound increases. He gasps for breath—covers it with a laugh. Rises. Argues about trifles in a high key, violent gesticulations.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
And the shutters—fastened each night—robbers, you understand—one cannot be too—

He paces the floor with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swings the chair he sat on and grates it upon the boards—wood shrieking—trying to bury the other sound.

The heartbeat grows louder—louder—louder—over all.

The men chat pleasantly. Smile.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Why would they not be gone? Oh God! what could I do? I foamed—I raved—I swore! I swung the chair upon which I had been sitting, and grated it upon the boards, but the noise arose over all and continually increased. It grew louder—louder—louder! And still the men chatted pleasantly, and smiled. Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!—this I thought, and this I think.

He stops. Face wild. The sound pounds—again—hark—louder—louder—louder—louder.

NARRATOR
(shrieking)
Villains! dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

He points at the floor beneath his feet—at the very boards.

The officers rise as one. The heartbeat thunders. Reynolds’s boot finds the seam of a plank.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

The Narrator alone again on the chair. Spent. The candle gutters. He stares at us—still, almost gentle—hearing something we cannot.

NARRATOR
How, then, am I mad?

A last faint pulse of that cotton-wrapped watch sound—somewhere—then nothing but the candle.

FADE OUT.

THE END
